#, no-wrap
msgid "MP3 Audio"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: documentation/content/en/books/handbook/multimedia/_index.adoc:346
msgid ""
"This section describes some `MP3` players available for FreeBSD, how to rip "
"audio `CD` tracks, and how to encode and decode ``MP3``s."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: documentation/content/en/books/handbook/multimedia/_index.adoc:348
#, no-wrap
msgid "MP3 Players"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: documentation/content/en/books/handbook/multimedia/_index.adoc:351
msgid ""
"A popular graphical `MP3` player is Audacious. It supports Winamp skins and "
"additional plugins. The interface is intuitive, with a playlist, graphic "
"equalizer, and more. Those familiar with Winamp will find Audacious simple "
"to use. On FreeBSD, Audacious can be installed from the "
"package:multimedia/audacious[] port or package. Audacious is a descendant of "
"XMMS."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: documentation/content/en/books/handbook/multimedia/_index.adoc:353
msgid ""
"The package:audio/mpg123[] package or port provides an alternative, "
"command-line `MP3` player. Once installed, specify the `MP3` file to play on "
"the command line. If the system has multiple audio devices, the sound device "
"can also be specified:"
msgstr ""

